|Cages which do not lie inside an object, ie (partly) surround the object, need special attention:&cr;&lf;&cr;&lf;|
|Construct a triangulated mesh consisting of the union of the object and the cage(s), eg by using Triangle. Use region markers to distinguish cage from object.|

|Remove all vertices (+ triangles) from the mesh which belong to the cage by using the region markers.&cr;&lf;See help patch for more info!|
|Also remove all rows from the blend weight matrix which belong to cage vertices.|
|NOTE: the size of the blend weight matrix is #Vertices rows X ((dim+1) * #Handles) columns. Here dim = 2. Therefore the Slicecount of the blend weight matrix spread is #Vertices * (3 * #Handles).|

|Cage edges simply are point handles which transform the mesh linearly along straight lines between the points. Therfore for cage edges&cr;&lf;- you need to specify every corner point of your cage as a point handle first&cr;&lf;- cage edge indices point into all specified point handle indices, starting with 0.&cr;&lf;|
|Handles = No. of point handles + number of bone edges; cage edges not taken into account, as they are special point handles and count as such.&cr;&lf;|

|In 2D, we need to add a 4th weight of 0 to our blend weight matrix.|
|Show cage|

|Like bones, cages require a sufficient amount of mesh vertices along cage edges, the more the better the result. This can be achieved by either manually adding these points along bone edges to Triangle (-> resample), or by using rather fine triangulations, like in this example. &cr;&lf;Note that manually adding them instead allows for less overall vertices in your mesh, hence better performance.|
|BoundedBiharmonicWeights does not work with duplicate vertices in a mesh, therefore we have to enable Unify.|
